Session II

The focus of this learninig session was on regression analysis. At initial step, to prepare the data for the analysis we needed to go through a data wrangling process. The target of the study from which the data has been analyzed was investigating the effect of learning approaches, e.g. suarface approach (in which students memorize the content of the course without understanding) on students’ achievements and performance. Here is the link to the data https://www.mv.helsinki.fi/home/kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt. The steps taken in data wrangling consisted of:

1. creating a data set with the variables age, gender, attitude, deep, stra, surf, and points. While the variable ‘points’ exihibit the output (students’ points in the exam), other variables are considered as the input. The variables ‘deep’, ‘stra’, and ‘surf’ were the results of the sum of some subscales. 2. taking the mean of the sum of the subscales by deviding the sum to the number of elements (subscales). This step was taken to scale the combination variables such as ‘deep’ to their original scale. 3. excluding the observations where the variable ‘points’ were zero. 4. saving the wrangled data in a csv file.

attitude <- lrn14$Attitude

points <- lrn14$Points

dataset1 <- cbind(deep,surf,stra,gender,age,attitude,points)

dataset1[points==0] <- NA

dataset2 <- dataset1[complete.cases(dataset1),]

write.csv(dataset2, file = "data.csv", quote = TRUE, row.names = F)

After investigating the dimension and variables in the dataset, we realize that it consists of 382 observations with 35 variables, e.g., school, activities, and absences. The data that have been acquired from two secondary schools in Portugal is about the performance of students. Four variables ‘famrel’,‘goout’,‘health’,and ‘G1’ have been selected to assess their relationship with the target variable ‘high_use’. My personal hypothesises about the variables are as follows:

1.farmel The better the family relationships are, the less the use of alcohol will be.

2.goout The more the student goes out with her/his friends, the more the alcohol use will be.

3.health The better the health status is, the less the alcohol use will be.

4.G3 The better the final grade is, the less the alcohol use will be.

z values higher than 2 indicate the significance in regression output, meaning that the corresponding variable is significant. This can be also reflected by p values (confidence interval). With respect to this point,the variables farmel (p = 0.01) and goout (p < 0.05) are signifant. The coefficient of the variable ‘farmel’ shows that an increase in this variable is associated with a decrease in the log odds of the variable high_use by 0.388 units (meaning better family relationship reduces the probability of high alcohol use). Furthermore, the increase of the variable ‘gooout’ is associated with an increase in the log odds of the output by 0.785 units (implying that the more the students go out with their peers, the higher the probability of their high alcohol use will be).

Chapter IV

Exploring “Boston” dataset

The dataset Boston has been retrieved from a study conducted by Harisson and Rubinfeld (1978) based on which a model was proposed to measure the tendency of the potential buyers to pay for the clean air. In parallel, the dataset provides us with the information regarding the crime rate (crim), nitrogen oxides concentration (nox), the percentage of individuals with low sociaeconomical status, and other variables that their descriptions can be found in the following link: https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html.

Checking the structure and dimension of the dataset, it was depicted that the dataset consists of 506 rows as observations and 17 columns as predictors.

Standardization of variables

As it has been observed earlier, some data points (outliers) in the variables cause the non-normal distribution. To overcome this issue, Z-score standardization has been implemented so that the data will have mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1. Furthermore, Normal distribution is a precondition of our further processing, that is, LDA. Following standardization of the data variables, we check the summary of the scaled data.

Correlation

The correlation matrix is of high importance in PCA analysis. Indeed, in PCA the most essential features (dimension) of a dataset are extracted and one of the main assumptions is that many features contribute to the same underlying dimension. Some features might contribute to the same To asses the relationship between the different variables, the correlation plots were used. The following figure summarized the results. As it can be observed, there was a strong, positive correlation between the two variables ‘Life.Exp’ and ‘Edu.Exp’(r = 0.789), meaning that the increase in schooling years is correlated with increase in life expectancy. Furthermore, the results demonstrated a strong negative correlation between ‘Life.Exp’ and ‘Mat.Mor’(r = 0.857), indicating that the increase in maternal mortality ratio was correlated with decrease in life expectancy. As it will be shown later, high correlations are of high importance in PCA.

Distribution

Distribution of the variables can be observed in the figure. While some variables including GNI and Mat.Mor are positive skewed, other variables are negatively skewed or normal distributed. The distribution (the mean and the standard deviation of the variables) are also another important factor in PCA.

Question II: Performing PCA on non-standardized dataset

First we perform the PCA analysis using the original (non-standardized) dataset. PCA biplots are frequently used to show the component scores and variable loading. The bottom axis represents the PC1 scores, while the left, top and left axes depict the PC2 scores, loading on PC1, and loading on PC2, respectively. The scores depict the observations in two dimensions, while the vectors show the original dimensions and their relationship with respect to each other and other PCs. Further the vectors are from the PC origin, the more the standard deviation of the feature is. Also, the angle between the vectors (including each variable and a PC axis) reveals information on correlation between the variables. If the angle between the vectors is small, their corresponding variables are highly correlated. If the angle is close to 90 degree, it implies that there is no correlation between the variables, while the angle close to 180 degrees shows a negative correlation. Since the highly correlated variables might be traced back to the same underlying component, they can be reduced to principle components.

Question III: Performing PCA on standardized dataset

PCA is performed to reduce dimension and this is performed via identifying the principle components. Based on PCA, the vectors (directions) with the largest variances are the features with the highest importance. Hence, if there are various variables with various variance, PCA loads on the ones with the largest variance. Furthermore, in dataset like the human dataset, the variables have been measured in different scales. Thereby, to avoid the output being affected by these issues and make the variables comparable, standardization is an essential step to be taken prior to applying to PCA. For instance, we can see from the figures that the PCA on the non-standardized dataset gives the loading on one variable.

##  PC1  PC2  PC3  PC4  PC5  PC6  PC7  PC8

Question IV: Interpretation of the PCA

Having the following variables in the dataset, we can see that there are some countries having higher rate of each of these variables. Those variables along the first PC (horizontal line) makes up the 53.6 % of the data and those along the second PC (vertical line) makes up 16.2 % of it.

“Country” = Country name “GNI” = Gross National Income per capita “Life.Exp” = Life expectancy at birth “Edu.Exp” = Expected years of schooling “Mat.Mor” = Maternal mortality ratio “Ado.Birth” = Adolescent birth rate “Parli.F” = Percetange of female representatives in parliament “Edu2.F” = Proportion of females with at least secondary education “Edu2.M” = Proportion of males with at least secondary education “Labo.F” = Proportion of females in the labour force “Labo.M” " Proportion of males in the labour force “Edu2.FM” = Edu2.F / Edu2.M “Labo.FM” = Labo2.F / Labo2.M

Along the first PC, the countries on the positive side have higher gross national income, life expectancy, expected years of schooling, and ratio of expected years of schooling in females. Whereas, those countries on the negative side have higher maternal mortality ration and adolscent birth rate.

Along the second PC, the countries towrds the positive side have higher percentage of female representatives in parliament and higher ratio of proportion of females to males in labour force.
